<TEXT>
all children in the united states especially 
those entering middle school or junior high school should be given 
a second vaccination against measles the american academy of 
pediatrics said 
the shot would be in addition to one that all children are 
supposed to receive when they are about 15 months old according to 
the academy headquartered in suburban elk grove village 
the warning issued by the academy monday comes with doctors 
fearing that measles infections in 1989 could be worse than in any 
of the past nine years 
many children are contracting the disease even though they were 
vaccinated as infants dr scott giebink of the university of 
minnesota said monday giebink is a member of the academys 
committee on infectious diseases 
the centers for disease control in atlanta has counted 7563 
measles cases throughout the nation this year up to july 9 a 376 
percent increase over the 1586 cases reported during the comparable 
period last year 
john mullen of the cdc said there are 30 outbreaks or clusters 
of measles cases in 19 states 
the majority of new cases are in children and young people from 
kindergarten through college giebink said 
about 60 percent were in children already vaccinated he said 
as a result the academy and the us public health service 
both now recommend two doses of the vaccine for all children in the 
united states he said 
</TEXT>
