the taxpayers investment in surplus farm 
commodities continues to show a sharp decline from last years 
levels largely as a result of droughtreduced crop production in 
1988 and rising market prices 
an agriculture department report released monday showed the 
commodity credit corp had 135 billion invested in price support 
loans and actual inventories as of may 31 that included 91 
billion in loans outstanding and 44 billion in governmentowned 
commodities said the report by keith bjerke the cccs executive 
vice president 
a year earlier on may 31 1988 the ccc had an investment of 
231 billion including 143 billion in loans outstanding and 88 
billion in inventories 
the ccc finances various price support operations of the 
department including those for wheat feed grains rice tobacco 
cotton soybeans dairy products honey and sugar 
in the case of the major grain crops the 1988 drought reduced 
production and pushed up prices that reduced the need for price 
support loans and forfeitures which means the ccc takes over 
ownership of crops when farmers opt not to repay the loans 
when market prices are high enough its usual for farmers to pay 
off the loans and use or sell as they choose 
the farmerowned grain reserve which enables wheat and feed 
grains to be stored and kept off the market under government loan 
until prices rise enough to trigger their release consisted of 287 
million bushels of wheat valued at more than 1 billion as of may 
31 the report said 
corn and other feed grains in the reserve totaled more than 103 
billion bushels valued at 257 billion 
the total value of commodities acquired by ccc in the first eight 
months of the fiscal year that began last oct 1 was 172 billion 
the report said in the same period of 198788 ccc acquired 
products valued at 962 billion 
net losses to ccc totaled about 352 billion through may 31 the 
report said compared with a loss of more than 10 billion in the 
same eight months of 198788 the decline was mainly due to the 
smaller volume of grain moving into ccc inventories and reduced 
payments to farmers 
dairy inventories held by ccc also continued to edge down from 
the high levels of a few years ago 
as of may 31 for example total holding were reported at 5676 
