nearly 100 boat captains protested the 
dredging of muck from the san francisco bay which they say is 
suffocating fish devastating the fishing industry and creating 
toxic hazards 
fishermen blew their horns and flew flags of protest on monday to 
call attention to the more than 10 million cubic yards of new 
sediment that ends up in the bay every year 
boats displayed banners that read stop choking our bay 
stop the dumping and muck kills 
bob martin 27 a recreational fisherman who has been fishing for 
striped bass in the san francisco bay since he was a young boy said 
he was worried by the decline of the fish 
right now its hardly worth fishing for them he said i 
just hope we get to the point that if i have kids someday i can tell 
them what a striped bass is instead of what it was 
we want the people of california to know and the politicians 
to know and the regional water board to know that our bay just 
cannot take anymore dumping of dredging spoils said keith fraser 
former president of the united anglers association we are at the 
saturation point 
but bill prout spokesman for the us army corps of engineers 
which does most of the bay dredging and oversees the rest defended 
dredging as a necessary means of maintaining shipping channels in 
the naturally muddy area 
weve been dredging here for 65 years and it hasnt killed off 
all the fish up to this point prout said the species here live 
in the turbid environment 
dredging critics also fear that an underground mountain of 
dredged muck west of alcatraz island poses a navigational and toxic 
hazard the alcatraz dump site is targeted for closure in december 
1991 but critics want it closed immediately 
critics said seals and sea lions already have fled the bay for 
cleaner water and striped bass and halibut populations have been 
way down in recent years 
demonstrators want the muck hauled up the sacramentosan joaquin 
delta to shore up levees or at least 25 miles out to sea where the 
ocean depth drops abruptly from a few hundred feet to at least 3000 
feet 
prout said it costs between 2 and 3 per cubic yard to haul 
sediment from the port of oakland to alcatraz compared to estimated 
costs of up to 8 per cubic yard to haul it out to seas 
theres not an easy answer to this problem he said 
denny larson of citizens for a better environment conceded that 
proposals to haul dredging spoils beyond the bay will be costly but 
he said keeping open the alcrataz dump site may pose greater costs 
dredging stirs up toxic chemicals like cadmium mercury nickel 
lead zinc and petroleum hydrocarbons said greg karras a toxicity 
specialist for citizens for a better environment 
karras said about 40 percent of all dumped material ends up 
recirculating in bay waters about 30 percent remains near alcatraz 
and another 30 percent is swept out to shallow ocean areas 
were creating toxic hot spots underwater karras said 
