<TEXT>
a judicial review has accepted an investigation 
that found that icy wings rather than a bomb caused a 1985 plane 
crash that killed 256 us servicemen and crew in gander 
newfoundland a newspaper said today 
the review found no need to reopen the case the paper said 
the canadian aviation safety board probe was controversial 
because five board members said icy wings caused the crash while 
the other four theorized that a bomb was to blame 
some board members also charged that evidence pointing to a 
terrorist attack was withheld 
sources at the safety board and department of transport said the 
review ordered in march by transport minister benoit bouchard 
generally exonerates the boards staff investigators the toronto 
globe and mail said 
the newspaper said in todays editions that the review written 
by justice willard estey a former supreme court of canada judge 
will be released friday 
the fivemember majority on the investigatory board found that a 
thin layer of ice reduced the lifting capacity of the wings of the 
arrow air jet causing the chartered aircraft to crash on takeoff on 
dec 12 1985 
the paper quoted sources as saying the review gives no credence 
to the bomb theory or to claims that evidence was withheld 
the dissenters suggested a coverup by canadian and us agencies 
sought to hide what they argued was a terrorist attack on the aging 
dc8 that was taking us troops home for christmas after a 
peacekeeping tour in the middle east 
no evidence of a bomb has ever been presented although the 
dissenters say its absence demonstrates the wideranging nature of 
the coverup 
safety board chairman ken thorneycraft refused monday to discuss 
esteys review he said he was unaware of its findings but added 
that he had always been confident that any independent assessment of 
the agencys investigation would conclude it was conducted 
thoroughly and reached reasonable conclusions 
critics of the icing finding including the us airline pilots 
association have accused the board of fabricating evidence in a bid 
to blame the planes pilots both pilots six other crew members and 
all 248 us servicemen on board died in the crash the worst ever 
in canada 
the globe and mail also said les filotas one of the boards 
dissenters sent a letter to estey saying arro air may have been 
involved in armsforhostages exchanges conducted secretly on 
behalf of highly placed individuals in the american administration 
and that if so there would have been strong motivation for 
attempts to confound aspects of the investigation 
