<TEXT>
the government said tuesday the us trade 
deficit widened sharply to 1024 billion in may as america brought 
in record imports sold less goods abroad and lost ground in its bid 
to shrink the trade gap 
mays imbalance was the biggest in five months and represented a 
236 percent increase over the 829 billion deficit registered in 
april when the nation had its smallest monthly trade gap in more 
than four years 
analysts predicted aprils figure was the low point for the year 
and said mays increase dealt a blow to hopes that the us trade 
deficit would improve significantly this year 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher called the latest report 
disappointing but said he was encouraged by the continuing 
strength of exports which declined slightly in may from a record 
high in april 
us trade representative carla hills said the report was 
consistent with our expectation that the trade deficit will 
continue to improve at a modest pace in 1989 
for the first five months of the year the trade gap was running 
at an annual rate of 1111 billion compared with an actual 1988 
deficit of 11853 billion last years figure was a 221 percent 
improvement over 1987 
the trade deficit over time and on average is improving but 
only slowly said economist allen sinai of the boston co we are 
light years away from anything resembling balance in our trade 
the nations best chance for trade improvement probably awaits 
a significant turn for the worse in the us economy which would 
cause american businesses and consumers to purchase fewer imports 
he said 
in may imports shot up 43 percent to a record 4071 billion 
boosted by a big increase in americas foreign oil bill and stronger 
spending on foreign agricultural products capital goods and 
industrial supplies 
petroleum imports surged 173 percent to 475 billion as both 
the price and volume of foreign oil purchases rose the average 
price for a barrel of oil rose for the sixth straight month and 
reached 1840 in may the volume of oil imports rose for the second 
straight month to 833 million barrels a day 
exports meanwhile dropped off 09 percent to 3047 billion 
reflecting slower foreign demand for us products in almost every 
major catogory led by a 57 percent drop in purchases of 
americanmade consumer goods 
analysts said exports are likely to decline further as the 
strength of the us dollar against other currencies increases the 
price of american goods on foreign markets 
economist michael evans head of a washington consulting firm 
said mays trade figure in part represented a bounceback from an 
artificially low april deficit but he predicted the monthly trade 
figures are likely to gradually increase for the rest of the year 
i wouldnt say this was just a fluke or that its going to get 
better again evans said we are going to see pretty sluggish 
exports this year and that is the result of the higher dollar 
bruce steinberg economist for merrill lynch capital markets in 
new york said the united states might make some modest progress on 
the trade gap later this year if the nations slowing economy pulls 
in fewer imports but nothing like the 34 billion improvement 
recorded in 1988 
i would describe the trade environment as intractable 
steinberg said its difficult to get a lot more improvement than 
weve seen 
the latest report showed increases in the us trade imbalances 
with most major trading partners 
as usual the united states posted its largest trade deficit in 
may with japan a 428 billion shortfall that was up from 389 
billion in april the nation posted a small 783 million deficit 
with western europe after registering surpluses in both march and 
april 
the imbalance with canada the largest us trading partner was 
7393 million in may up from 1748 million in april other large 
deficits in may were recorded with taiwan 109 billion south 
korea 503 million and mexico 452 million 
