<TEXT>
tom fenton publisher of the el paso texas 
times was an associated press correspondent in nicaragua during the 
final days of the somoza regime he recalls the time in this account 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
managua was a place of fear and confusion in the last days of 
anastasio somozas regime it was a smoky noisy intensely 
dangerous city with few safe havens 
smoldering tires and pavingstone barricades turned streets into 
obstacle courses where ambushers might lurk looters smashed shop 
windows renegade soldiers and guerrillas relieved the unarmed and 
unwary of watches wallets and jewelry 
bombs demolished restaurants teenage snipers some shorter than 
their rifles played hitandrun with somozas army 
white flags flew from automobile antennas drivers hoped that 
would make them less of a target but it seldom worked 
somozas air force attacked guerrilla concentrations inside the 
city strafing rocketing even rolling bombs out of helicopters 
at las mercedes airport east of the city somoza supporters and 
their families tried desperately to get on departing flights somoza 
stayed in his bunker 
reporting became especially difficult and dangerous in may 1979 
sandinistas infiltrated the city you never knew when you would run 
into soldiers or guerrillas or how they would react 
journalists like combat troops learned to gauge situations by 
watching people in the street normal movement meant it was safe to 
proceed scurrying usually meant danger if no one was about the 
area probably was in someones field of fire 
we learned to watch for flaring nostrils on soldiers or 
guerrillas a sign of extreme agitation that meant it was time to 
leave if you could 
a chance encounter with irritable soldiers in managua cost abctv 
correspondent bill stewart his life stewart and his interpreter in 
the country only a few days were shot to death at an army 
checkpoint 
his crew recorded his death in dramatic television footage 
stewart was forced to his knees then made to lie face down in the 
street a corporal put the muzzle of his m16 to the back of the 
correspondents head and blew it away 
soldiers realized their mistake when they opened stewarts rented 
van and saw the american film crew a quickwitted nicaraguan driver 
saved their lives by suggesting to the soldiers that the murder be 
blamed on sandinistas 
the body was put into the van and stewarts crew returned to the 
intecontinental hotel just 200 yards from somozas bunker 
in case the army came to seize the tapes the abc crew made 
duplicates and passed them out to journalists in hopes at least one 
would be smuggled out of the country 
it was unnecessary abc transmited the tape to new york from 
sozomas satellite ground station before nicaraguan officials 
realized what it contained 
stewarts death was shown across the world and hastened the end 
of the somoza regime it also caused an evacuation of american 
journalists 
a us air force c130 arrived and took about 25 journalists 
most of them network television people and some american dependents 
to panama those who remained had the curious uncomfortable task of 
reporting the evacuation of our colleagues 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890718-0130 </DOCNO>
