<TEXT>
rapidly rising prescription drug prices may 
soon affect health care for the elderly members of the senate 
special committee on aging said tuesday 
steadily rising prescription prices have been driving up the 
costs of medicaid programs across the country and are a concern as 
well for the medicare program some lawmakers are concerned that the 
medicare drug benefit which takes effect in 1991 may already be 
underfunded 
from 1981 through 1988 the prescription drug inflation rate of 
88 percent dwarfed the general inflation rate of 28 percent said 
sen david pryor the committee chairman 
sen richard shelby dala said that soon many elderly will 
be priced out of the market 
sen herbert kohl dwis worried that senior citizens are 
already getting squeezed out and are not having their 
prescriptions filled or are cutting their doses to make their drugs 
last longer 
manufacturers claim they need exhorbitant prices in order to 
pay for their research and development expenses pryor said the 
truth is though that the american public is footing much of the 
bill for drug companies research expenses 
pryor also released a report by the panels democratic staff 
members showing that most of the new drugs pharmaceutical companies 
put on the market are duplicates of drugs already being sold 
that report found that 84 percent of the 348 new drugs brought to 
market by the 25 largest pharmaceutical companies between 1981 and 
1988 were judged by the food and drug administration as providing 
little or no therapeutic potential to improve on existing drugs 
the committee staff also said that hospitals and the department 
of veterans affairs get the best prices for prescription drugs 
sometimes paying several times less than prices charged by 
pharmacies where medicaid and medicare patients get most of their 
medications 
winston barton secretary of the kansas department of social and 
rehabilitation services said his state has kept medicaid 
prescription costs down with a bidding procedure under the program 
drug manufacturers bid for a contract that ensures the company 
volume sales and the state discounted prices 
but barton said the program has met with significant resistance 
from the pharmaceutical industry because the discounts cut into 
profits 
the pharmaceutical companies are the only entity in the health 
care field that do not pay their fair share in meeting the 
healthcare needs of the poor of this country barton testified 
the department of veterans affairs also negotiates for discounted 
prices for drugs it distributes but dennis m styrsky chief of the 
departments pharmaceutical products division said success is 
unfortunately very limited because some drug companies wont 
participate 
most of the drug companies asked to testify refused pryor said 
gerald mossinghoff president of the pharmaceutical manufacturers 
association defended the industry saying its share of the 
healthcare dollar dropped from more than 12 percent in 1965 to just 
under 7 percent in 1987 
drug prices he said reflect extensive research and development 
commitments which have doubled every five years since 1970 
mossinghoff said costs for labor materials product promotion and 
taxes have also grown 
also he said companies have had to shorten the time during 
which they recover their research expenses because of the surge in 
genericdrug competition that comes when a brandname drug patent 
expires 
