<TEXT>
the energy department said tuesday it will 
decide within two weeks when to restart the first of three 
deactivated nuclear reactors in south carolina that are the nations 
only source of a gas needed to make nuclear weapons 
john tuck the undersecretary of energy told reporters the 
department was in the final stages of working out details of a 
restart timetable with westinghouse savannah river which operates 
the savannah river reactors under a federal contract 
within a couple of weeks not far beyond the first of august 
the restart date will be set he said adding that the timetable 
would be coupled with announcement of a broader plan for ensuring 
safer and cleaner operation of the plant 
the three savannah river reactors near aiken sc are the sole 
source of tritium a radioactive isotope of hydrogen that is needed 
in the manufacture of thermonuclear warheads the three were closed 
down last year for technical and safety reasons 
early resumption of tritium production is considered crucial 
because supplies are falling the material must be periodically 
replaced in weapons in order to maintain their effectiveness the 
exact size of the tritium stockpile is classified but the pentagon 
said earlier this year that a supply squeeze was imminent 
tuck commented after testifying before a special panel of the 
house armed services committee that is assessing a variety of 
problems at the nuclear weapons complex which includes 17 major 
facilities in 12 states these plants design test and produce 
nuclear weapons and are operated by private companies under federal 
contract 
tuck said energy secretary james d watkins is strongly opposed 
to a bill sponsored by sen timothy wirth dcolo and a companion 
bill in the house sponsored by rep ron wyden dore that would 
transfer authority for studying the health effects of radiation on 
workers to the department of health and human services 
tuck said watkins wanted to retain that authority within his 
department 
to excuse doe from the responsibility of conducting 
epidemiologic surveys of its work force would be to excuse it from a 
key element of its responsibility to protect the health and safety 
of its workers tuck said 
wirth said the energy department should not be trusted to assess 
the health effects of radiation since it is a promoter of nuclear 
energy and weapons production 
this appearance of the fox guarding the chicken coop has 
inevitably led to a dramatic failure to win employee and public 
