commerce secretary robert mosbacher will decide 
soon whether to modify controversial regulations requiring shrimpers 
to equip their nets with turtleexcluder devices a spokesman said 
tuesday 
shrimpers claim the devices designed to keep endangered sea 
turtles from being tangled and killed in their nets also keep out a 
substantial portion of their catch because of clogging by debris and 
seaweed 
while opponents of the devices want mosbacher to continue 
suspending enforcement of the regulations until a study on the 
devices is completed by the national academy of sciences in 
february commerce spokesman brian gorman said that did not appear 
likely 
the coast guard last week ordered enforcement of the regulations 
be suspended pending mosbachers decision while the commerce 
department has its own enforcement force it relies on coast guard 
vessels for the atsea inspections 
there is not a whole lot that can be done in terms of a 
wholesale suspension of the regulations said gorman citing a 
federal court ruling upholding the law and a public comment period 
on the devices before their implementation 
gorman said the judge who upheld the law involving the devices 
us district court judge patrick carr of new orleans also agreed 
the regulations are not subject to the pending study 
mosbacher however has asked for a survey of the gulf coast to 
determine whether sargassum grass is a problem 
shrimpers claim an enormous infestation of this seaweed along 
the coast is clogging the nets and rendering the devices 
ineffective and causing a large loss of shrimp gorman said 
the survey he said began at the beginning of the month and an 
interim report is due within the next couple of days mosbacher will 
decide by weeks end or next week whether the regulations can be 
in some small way modified he said 
like the devices themselves the survey by the national marine 
fisheries service is controversial with rep solomon ortiz 
dtexas saying he is dissatisfied with the way the tests are being 
conducted 
ortiz said nets are being brought in after 20 minutes rather 
than being kept in the water for three or four hours as shrimpers 
would 
i dont think this is comparable to fishing conditions and of 
course theyre going to get different results ortiz said 
ortiz and other lawmakers said the devices reduce a shrimpers 
catch by 17 percent to 35 percent but with the recent seaweed 
infestation losses could reach 50 percent 
