<TEXT>
a guerrilla organization seeking 
independence for namibia acknowledged tuesday that some of its 
members may have entered the territory but denied it was preparing a 
largescale incursion 
leaders of the southwest africa peoples organization told a 
news conference that louis pienaar administratorgeneral of 
namibia told foreign diplomats friday that 1900 armed swapo 
guerrillas were in angola near namibias northern border and 
appeared prepared to launch an incursion namibia also is known as 
southwest africa 
swapos international liaison officer theoben gurirab said 
small infiltrations by swapo members may be taking place 
it is possible that there could be individuals or very small 
groups of two or three in southern angola or northern namibia he 
said it is possible we are dealing with humans but all 
fighters have been instructed to return north of the 16th parallel 
in angola 
the dispute over possible guerrilla movements came as un 
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar arrived for three days of 
meetings to assess progress of the unsupervised independence plan 
in africas last colony ruled by south africa for 74 years 
today un resolution 435 is being implemented in earnest 
perez de cuellar said of the independence plan 
i want to ensure that there will conditions for the holding of 
free and fair elections he said in a brief statement upon arrival 
at the windhoek airport from lisbon portugal 
he said critical problems remain but did not elaborate 
perez de cuellar did not mention the allegations that swapo might 
be planning to invade namibia or gurirabs accusation that pienaar 
was creating war hysteria 
jacobus venter of namibias foreign affairs department said 
military intelligence indicated swapo guerrillas in groups ranging 
from 80 to 480 were massed in more than a dozen locations just 
north of the namibianangolan border 
in a letter friday to the top united nations official in namibia 
martti ahtisaari venter said the groups were armed wearing 
uniforms and had taken their rucksacks and equipment with them 
a copy of the letter also was sent to several foreign observer 
missions in namibia including the united states the soviet union 
france west germany and britain 
a joint swapoun delegation with angolan and tanzanian 
observers traveled to northern namibia on saturday to investigate 
the allegations un spokesman fred eckhard reported monday no 
evidence was found of infiltrations or largescale concentrations of 
swapo fighters 
pienaar also said in a statement issued monday that the 
situation was calm and under full control on both sides of the 
border 
gurirab denied there was an impending invasion and called the 
report an attempt by the administration to malign swapo 
as a result of this war hysteria several heads of state and 
government were awakened to be informed of an imminent crisis facing 
the namibian independence process he told the news conference 
under the un independence plan for namibia swapo guerrillas 
are allowed to return as unarmed refugees to take part in the 
november elections which swapo is favored to win after fighting a 
23year guerrilla war against south african forces 
however armed guerrillas are to remain at swapo bases north of 
the 16th parallel about 100 miles north of the namibian border 
namibias south african administration claims swapo guerrillas 
are south of that line but swapos statement said there is no 
swapo military presence south of the 16th parallel or in the 
northern part of this country 
