<TEXT>
a replica of a civil warera sailing ship 
became trapped in ice in the north atlantic and later sank in rough 
seas but the seven crew members were rescued the ships builder 
said 
the sheila yeates a topsail ketch with an oak frame and a 
50foot deck left duluth on may 15 through the great lakes and st 
lawrence seaway bound for cornwall england 
it was one of the tall ships that commemorated the us 
bicentennial and had made numerous other voyages since then 
including one in 1985 from duluth to greenland but this was to have 
been its first atlantic crossing 
geoffrey pope 76 of excelsior who built and skippered the 
ship gave an account of the ships last voyage and sinking to 
friends in the minneapolis area monday from aboard the danish shrimp 
boat kiviuq which plowed through ice and dense fog friday to save 
the crew 
i feel very responsible pope said i lost the ship but 
aside from that i feel such a reaffirmation of the potential of 
the bond that exists between men in extremus 
pope said the voyage went smoothly until thursday at a point 
about 80 miles south of greenlands point farwell when they 
encountered ice farther south than expected 
the ship was soon engulfed in thick fog and surrounded by massive 
chunks of ice with no room to maneuver the shifting ice would have 
crushed the wooden ship pope said 
a lifeboat wouldnt have survived for two seconds he said 
it was kind of a mental hell there was no escape this was the 
end 
early friday the crew awakened pope and urged him to radio a 
mayday appeal for help 
the kiviuq which fishes in the arctic and is equipped with 
icebreaking equipment responded and found the sheila yeates within 
hours 
the trawler freed the sailing vessel and towed it 430 miles 
pope said he thought the ship could be repaired within a month 
but that was before rough water made the ship take on water it was 
finally cut loose and sank monday he told fellow sailing enthusiast 
tim carlson of plymouth 
the sheila yeates was designed by robert jackson of hopkins and 
was built in lunenburg nova scotia it was launched a month before 
opsail the july 1976 sailing extravaganza in new york harbor 
more than a dozen investors sank 150000 into the vessel just to 
get it launched six times their original estimates it was insured 
for 150000 by lloyds of london less than onethird what it would 
cost to replace it according to pope 
</TEXT>
