<TEXT>
angola was expected to become the 152nd member 
of the international monetary fund despite an announcement by the 
state department on tuesday that the united states voted against it 
the us has made clear that it could not support angolan 
membership in the fund at this time and we voted against the 
membership resolution the state department said 
the united states has strong influence in the fund but less than 
19 percent of the voting power international monetary sources who 
spoke on condition they not be quoted said none of the other 
members has indicated that it would vote against the southwest 
african country 
one source said the united states was apparently willing to let 
itself be outvoted and that a strong us position against angola 
could have delayed consideration 
a spokesman for the fund said he could make no statement now 
that an announcement would come in about a week the last votes are 
due by telex wednesday at the funds headquarters in washington 
approval of angolas membership in the fund would normally clear 
the way for it also to become the 152nd member of the funds sister 
organization the world bank 
us administrations have opposed fund membership for angola 
because of its marxist government and supported the rebel unita 
movement of jonas savimbi on june 22 savimbi and the government of 
president jose eduardo dos santos agreed on a ceasefire 
the funds basic job is to keep currencies stable to do that it 
makes loans in recent years largely to third world countries 
the borrowing governments promise in return to make belttightening 
changes in policy so as to put their economies into better shape to 
repay 
some of these changes have resulted in hardships for their 
people devaluation of a borrowing countrys currency which the 
fund often calls for makes imported goods more expensive cuts in 
government spending another frequent requirement often result in 
cuts of subsidies on food and other basic articles and consequently 
high prices for consumers 
riots earlier this year in venezuela and jordan were linked to 
policies undertaken at the funds suggestion 
fund officials say that unless borrowing governments adopt such 
policies their overall situation will grow even worse 
increasingly the world bank has made similar structural 
adjustment loans but the bulk of its lending is for specific 
projects such as schools roads farming and health care which 
contribute directly to raising a countrys standard of living 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

