<TEXT>
if a doctor says you need an angioplasty 
heres a word of advice from the experts make sure your physician 
is competent 
how ask lots of questions 
many people are reluctant to challenge their physicians skill at 
doing the procedure perhaps because they fear the doctor will be 
insulted 
people spend more time in los angeles searching out the right 
restaurants than the right person to perform a procedure that 
potentially threatens their lives said dr stephen oesterle of 
good samaritan hospital 
but top cardiologists say that good practitioners will not be put 
off by reasonable questions here are some to ask 
how many angioplasties have you done 
experts say 50 a year is a bare minimum to keep up competence 
several cardiologists said they would not have the procedure done on 
themselves by doctors who perform fewer than 200 annually 
do you routinely do angioplasties in cases as complicated as 
mine 
a single narrowing in one heart artery is easier to treat than 
multiple blockages in several arteries if your problem is complex 
make sure the doctor has already successfully handled similar cases 
what is your success rate 
doctors who specialize in angioplasty are routinely able to 
initially open up 95 percent or more of blocked arteries about 3 
percent of their patients require emergency bypass surgery and less 
than 1 percent die 
will a skilled team of heart surgeons be waiting in case 
something goes wrong 
surgical backup in the same hospital is considered mandatory 
are there are other options that might be better for me 
alternatives to angioplasty can include medicine bypass surgery 
or no treatment at all dont hesitate to get a second opinion if 
you have any doubts about whether angioplasty is necessary 
</TEXT>
