<TEXT>
miners in western siberia will not end their 
crippling weeklong strike despite a pledge by politburo member 
nikolai slyunkov to increase food and consumer supplies a spokesman 
for the miners said today 
the work stoppage in the kuznetsk basin in western siberia has 
spread to the nations largest coal mining region the donetsk coal 
basin in the ukraine 
workers threw down their tools at two more mines in the donetsk 
where 15 shafts are idle a member of the strike committee said 
that job action began saturday but was not disclosed until monday 
slyunkov flew to the kuznetsk basin and met with the strikers 
monday night and today in an effort to resolve the walkout by more 
than 112000 miners there 
slyunkov addressed 30000 people at midday in the main square of 
prokopievsk 2100 miles east of moscow 
valery legachev a spokesman for the regional strike committee in 
siberia said slyunkov promised to increase food and consumer 
supplies but legachev said miners there were continuing their 
walkout because slyunkov was not specific 
in moscow the supreme soviet speeded up work on legislation on 
resolving labor conflicts 
the offical news agency tass carried a report denying that the 
thirdlargest coal region karaganda in kazakhstan was also on 
strike 
in the first kremlin comment on the strike premier nikolai i 
ryzhkov said monday that it threatened production at some 
metallurgical and power plants 
weekend press reports said coal production had been cut by 1 
million tons and a coal shortage had interrupted work at the 
magnitka steel complex in the ural mountains 
in meetings with strikers slyunkov promised higher pay for night 
work longer vacations and a doubling of the wholesale price of 
coal the government newspaper izvestia reported in todays editions 
but the strike committee spokesman said the promises lacked 
substance and the miners would stay out until all their demands were 
met 
we are determined to go on with the strike because they 
received no concrete documented response to their demands 
legachev said there were only general statements 
he promised to increase the areas regular food supplies by 20 
to 30 percent as well as soap and washing powder legachev said 
the miners from prokopievsk and eight other towns in the kuznetz 
basin are demanding greater economic autonomy from the moscowbased 
coal mining ministry 
in makeyevka in the donetsk region strike committee leader 
vladimir komissaruk said the strike spread today to two more mines 
it is like a chain reaction komissaruk said in a telephone 
interview from strike committee headquarters 
miners in the donetsk basin or donbass are demanding a 40 
percent wage increase for night work improved living conditions a 
fixed day off and retirement after 20 years of underground work 
they also demanded that the mining ministry trim its managerial 
staff 
no law deals with industrial strikes which were suppressed in 
the soviet union before the reforms launched by president mikhail s 
gorbachev four years ago 
underground journals have described work stoppages that were far 
shorter and not as widespread as the coal strike which appeared to 
be the worst labor unrest in the soviet union since the turbulence 
of the 1920s 
a draft law on ending strikes and other labor conflicts is being 
pushed through the supreme soviet legislature tass said today 
the draft was being studied by the committee on legislation 
legality and law and order which received the proposed legislation 
monday tass said 
their opinion is that the draft will furnish a legal basis for 
a resolution of labor conflicts including the current largescale 
coal miners strike tass said 
