<TEXT>
imported foods that dont meet us standards 
regularly find their way to american dinner tables because 
government inspectors lack the resources to enforce federal 
regulations a congressional staff report said tuesday 
importers often exploit the weaknesses in the food and drug 
administrations inspection system and the lack of coordination 
between fda and the customs service to get substandard products onto 
the us market said the staff report of the house energy and 
commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations 
moreover the report said the chance that violators will be 
caught is slim and even when they are caught the penalties are so 
slight that violators view them as nothing more than a minor cost 
of doing business 
in 1987 the fda tested 2 percent of more than 1 million 
shipments of imported food the investigators wrote some 40 percent 
of the tested samples did not meet fda standards for reasons 
including contamination with salmonella pesticides insects and 
filth 
one cannot but wonder how many contaminated importations are 
overlooked the report said 
the subcommittee begins a series of hearings wednesday into the 
governments foodimport regulations 
the fda in responding to the report said it exaggerated some of 
the problems but the report is nevertheless correct in showing 
that increased imports have strained the federal governments system 
for sampling testing and blocking some questionable imports fda 
however has worked with the us customs service to coordinate our 
priorities and protect the public health 
the report details the ease with which shipments that are tested 
and rejected by the fda can still end up being sold to us 
consumers 
the fdas import operations branch in a march 1988 study cited 
by the congressional report estimated that more than 12 percent of 
all refused shipments got onto the us market anyway 
for instance importers sometimes give customs officials fake 
documentation purporting to show that rejected goods were destroyed 
when in fact they were sold to us distributors illegally 
another way importers evade the system is to port shop when 
a shipment is rejected the importer can take his goods to another 
port of entry and try again 
an example cited in the report occurred in puerto rico where the 
fda district office instituted an intensive examination of all 
shellfish over a sixweek period inspectors found that 75 percent 
of the shipments did not meet federal standards mostly from 
decomposition shellfish imports dropped dramatically 
san juan believed its efforts to improve shellfish quality had 
succeeded but subsequently found decomposed shellfish in the food 
distribution system the report said san juan concluded that 
the shellfish they refused to admit were entered at a mainland port 
and shipped back to puerto rico 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

