<TEXT>
police said they have rearrested the president of a 
machinery company for allegedly selling restricted semiconductor 
manufacturing equipment to east germany 
a police official speaking on condition of anonymity monday 
said hirokuni matsuda president of prometron technics corp 
exported the equipment valued at the equivalent of 98600 via 
south korea and china in 1987 without governmental approval 
the equipment a mask aligner produced by canon inc of japan is 
used in etching integrated circuits onto silicon plates it is on a 
list of items restricted by the coordinating committee on 
multilateral export control or cocom a parisbased organization 
that regulates western trade in strategic items with the communist 
bloc 
on july 7 police arrested matsuda for allegedly supplying east 
germany in 1986 and 1987 with more than 22 pounds of hafnium a rare 
material that can be used in nuclear reactor rods hafnium also is 
on the cocom list 
while questioning matsuda about the first violation 
investigators discovered the semiconductor case the official said 
he said prometron a tokyobased maker of air plasma steel 
cutters set up a subsidiary in south korea allegedly to purchase 
the equipment from canon on june 27 1987 the subsidiary allegedly 
shipped it to east germany via shanghai china the official said 
he said police rearrested matsuda on charges of violating japans 
trade control law customs laws and foreign exchange laws if 
convicted he could be sentenced to up to five years in prison 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

